  <title>Using Recurring/Repeating tasks</title>

  <p>Repeating tasks are the tasks that must be done many times on a fixed perid (day, week, month, year). By making a task repeat, the due date will hold the date on which the task must be completed. If a start date is set, the occurence of that task will begin from that date.</p> 

<section id="set-recurring-tasks">
<title>How to set a task to repeat</title>

<p>There are three ways to do so.<gui>The Quick Add Entry</gui> is the fastest with the simple keyword <em style="strong">every<em>. Furthermore, you can also use the <gui>Task Editor</gui>(from the circular button) and the context menu</p>

<note stlye="tip"><p>In the task Editor, the circular button will light blue to notify you when the task is recurring. In the taskview, you will also have a similar icon.</p></note>
</section>
 
<section id="valid-recurring-terms">
<title>What are the valid recurring terms</title>

<p>The valid terms are very similar to <link href="gtg-date-parsing">Keyword Parsing Syntax</link> for start and due dates with the exception of some few keywords</p>
<table rules="rows" frame="top bottom" ui:expanded="true">
<title>Recurring term Syntax</title>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <td><p><em style="strong">Syntax</em></p></td>
      <td><p><em style="strong">Example</em></p></td>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><p><code>yyyy-mm-dd</code> or <code>yyyy/mm/dd</code></p></td>
      <td><p>2020-04-01 or 2020/04/01. This will repeat every year on 04/01.</p></td>
    </tr>
<tr>
      <td><p><code>yyyymmdd</code></p></td>
      <td><p>20200401 This will repeat every year on 04/01.</p></td>
    </tr>
<tr>
      <td><p><code>mmdd</code></p></td>
      <td><p>0401 (with the year being assumed as the current one). This will repeat every year on 04/01.</p></td>
    </tr>
<tr>
          <td><p><code>day</code></p></td>
          <td><p>With this syntax, the task repeats daily.</p></td>
        </tr>
<tr>
        <td><p><code>other-day</code></p></td>
        <td><p>With this syntax, the task repeats every other day.</p></td>
        </tr>
<tr>
        <td><p><code>week</code></p></td>
        <td><p>Will repeat every week on the same day that the task was set.</p></td>
                </tr>
<tr>
        <td><p><code>month</code></p></td>
        <td><p>Will repeat monthly.</p></td>
        </tr>
<tr>
        <td><p><code>year</code></p></td>
        <td><p>Will repeat yearly.</p></td>
        </tr>
<tr>
        <td><p><code>Monday</code> (or any day of the week)</p></td>
        <td><p>Will repeat on that day of the week</p></td>
        </tr>
<tr>
      <td><p><code>27</code> (or any day's number)</p></td>
      <td><p>In this example, the task will recur on every 27 of the month.</p></td>
    </tr>
</tbody>
</table>

</section>
 <section id="recurring-examples">
<title>Recurring Examples</title>
<p>The following shows examples of how recurring terms work. These examples are made using the <gui>Quick Add Entry</gui> but do not deffer in results from the Task Editor.</p>

<terms>
  <item>
     <title><em style="strong"><code>pay my taxes every:year</code></em></title>
        <p>This task will repeat every year on the date which the task was created.</p></item>
  <item>
     <title><em style="strong"><code>Go out with my dog every:day start:next month</code></em></title>
        <p>By setting a start date, this task will not recurr every date from today's date but from the start date</p></item>
</terms>
</section>
